ce:section.ce:para:
To deeply understand the possible mechanism of the fluorescence response of GQDs with mixed-valence states metal ions, we performed density functional theory (DFT) computations of Fe3+/Fe2+, Cr3+/Cr2+, and Cu2+/Cu+ ions adsorbed on GQDs, to reveal the interaction between GQDs and metal ions with different valence states at a molecular level. Here, C54H18 (C54) was selected as the GQD model, and binary M@C54 systems (M = Fe3+, Fe2+, Cr3+, Cr2+, Cu2+, and Cu+) were optimised at the B3LYP-D3/6–31 g(d) level. Calculation results show that the structures with ions located at the centre of the ring have the lowest energies in each system (see Fig. 6
                        ). For the Fe2+@C54 and Fe3+@C54 systems, the binding energies were −309.20 and −705.66 kcal/mol, with corresponding partial charge transfers (from C54 to ions) of 1.12 and 2.12 e, respectively. Obviously, the adsorption interactions of Fe3+ and Fe2+ with GQDs are significantly different. This is also supported by the results of our UV–vis experiments, where the intensity of GQDs in Fe3+ solution decreased at 282 nm (n-π* transition) and slightly decreased at 228 nm (π-π* transition) compared with that in pure water, while the intensity of GQDs in Fe2+ solution was almost unchanged (see Fig. 7
                        ). In addition, we further performed a natural energy decomposition analysis (NEDA) of the binding energy, where the binding energy was decomposed into electrical interaction (EL), charge transfer (CT), and core repulsion (Core). As shown in Fig. 6b, the adsorption interaction between C54 and ions originates from EL and CT, and the significant difference between the Fe2+@C54 and Fe3+@C54 systems was mainly due to CT, consistent with the result of the partial charge transfer. As with Fe3+/Fe2+, the M@C54 systems (M = Cr3+/Cr2+ and Cu2+/Cu+) also had similar results, i.e., the stronger binding energies and more electron transfer (about 1 e) for the high-valence metal ions (see Fig. 6c-6f). Thus, the high selectivity and fast response in our experiments were attributable to the photoluminescence of GQDs being highly sensitive to the charge transfer between metal ions and GQDs.
